#Now I want to create the function for my barplots
#Note I just used the same basic code from Project INN Final
# Next we want to create function to create labeled bargraphs

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # This is the length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))
        
    plt.xticks(rottion=90, fontsize = 12)   
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette='viridis',
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # This is the percentage of each class for the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # this is the number of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # the width of the graph
        y = p.get_height()  # the height of the graph

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points"
        )  # shows us the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale
#I used the same code from the Project 4 INN

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(16, 6), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Combines boxplot and histogram

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (16,6))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)}, #These are the heigh ratios
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="aqua"
    )  # boxplot will be created and an asterisk will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

#Making sure we have our imports that we need
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
In [56]:
#Since we have our imports, lets define our clusters and plot them
clusters=range(1, 10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters: 
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(sub_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(sub_scaled_df)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(sub_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1))
                          /sub_scaled_df.shape[0])
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average Distortion')
plt.title('Selecting K with Elbow Method')
Out[56]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting K with Elbow Method')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Fit KMeans model and provide silhouette scores for range of K Clusters
silhouette_scores = []  # Renamed to avoid conflict
cluster_list = range(2, 10)

for n_clusters in cluster_list: 
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=42)
    prediction = clusterer.fit_predict(sub_scaled_df)
    score = silhouette_score(sub_scaled_df, prediction)  # Calculate silhouette score
    silhouette_scores.append(score)  # Append score to the list
    print(f"For n_clusters = {n_clusters}, the silhouette score is {score}")

# Plot the silhouette scores
plt.plot(cluster_list, silhouette_scores, marker='o')
plt.title("Silhouette Score vs Number of Clusters")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

#The next part of the project is Hierarchical clustering
#First lets create a list of the distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]
#Then lets create a list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics: 
    for lm in linkage_methods: 
        Z = linkage(sub_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, cophenet_distances = cophenet(Z, pdist(sub_scaled_df))
        print(
            "The Cophenetic Correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, round(c, 2)
            )
        )
        print("")
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

In [79]:
#We have to create a dendrogram
# Create a list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# List to save results of cophenetic correlation calculations
compare_cophenetic_correlations = []

# Subplot image for multiple dendrograms
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(10, 20))
fig.tight_layout(pad=5.0)

# Loop through linkage methods
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    # Perform linkage
    Z = linkage(sub_scaled_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)
    
    # Plot dendrogram
    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")
    
    # Calculate cophenetic correlation
    cophenetic_corr, cophenetic_distances = cophenet(Z, pdist(sub_scaled_df))
    compare_cophenetic_correlations.append((method, cophenetic_corr))
    
    # Annotate cophenetic correlation on the subplot
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic Correlation: {cophenetic_corr:0.2f}", 
        xy=(0.70, 0.90), 
        xycoords="axes fraction", 
        fontsize=10, 
        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round", facecolor="white", edgecolor="black")
    )

# Display the plot
plt.show()

# Print cophenetic correlations
print("Cophenetic Correlations for Linkage Methods:")
for method, corr in compare_cophenetic_correlations:
    print(f"{method.capitalize()} Linkage: {corr:.2f}")

Cophenetic Correlations for Linkage Methods:
Single Linkage: 0.92
Complete Linkage: 0.79
Average Linkage: 0.94
Centroid Linkage: 0.93
Ward Linkage: 0.71
Weighted Linkage: 0.87

#Finally we want to create a box plot of numerical variables for each Hierarchical cluster
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 3, figsize=(30, 30))
counter = 0

for ii in range(4):
    for jj in range (3): 
        if counter < 10:
            sns.boxplot(
                ax=axes[ii][jj], 
                data = df_hierarchy, 
                y=df.columns[3+counter], 
                x="Hierarchical_clusters", 
                palette="Paired"
            )
            counter = counter + 1
fig.tight_layout(pad=3.0)

#3 The stocks in this cluster have the highest ROE
#4: The stocks in this clsuter have some of the lowest net income.

#3: This cluster is pretty evenly distributed among sectors. 
#4: It has one of the highest earning per share
#5: As expected, there are several outliers.

#2: The breakdowns of sector of this stock is quite disproportionate, as 91% or 20 belong to Energy
#The only two other sectors present in this Cluster are IT(1) and Materals(1).
